  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref1" name="_ftn1" class="fn" id="_ftn1">[1]</a> Formal Charges, July 12,
  2001.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref2" name="_ftn2" class="fn" id="_ftn2">[2]</a> State Bar Articles of
  Incorporation, Art. 16, Rules of Prof.Conduct, Rule 1.3, LSA-R.S. foll. 37:221</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">Rule 1.3. Diligence</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">&nbsp; A lawyer shall act with reasonable diligence and promptness in representing a client.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref3" name="_ftn3" class="fn" id="_ftn3">[3]</a> State Bar Articles of
  Incorporation, Art. 16, Rules of Prof.Conduct, Rule 1.4, LSA-R.S. foll. 37:221</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">Rule 1.4. Communication</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">&nbsp; (a) A lawyer shall keep a client reasonably informed about the status of a matter and
  promptly comply with reasonable requests for information.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">&nbsp; (b) The lawyer shall give the client sufficient information to participate intelligently in
  decisions concerning the objectives of the representation and the means by which they are to be pursued, to the
  extent the client is willing and able to do so.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref4" name="_ftn4" class="fn" id="_ftn4">[4]</a> State Bar Articles of
  Incorporation, Art. 16, Rules of Prof.Conduct, Rule 3.2, LSA-R.S. foll. 37:221</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">Rule 3.2. Expediting litigation</p>

  <p class="footnotetext">&nbsp; A lawyer shall make reasonable efforts to expedite litigation consistent with the interests
  of the client.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref5" name="_ftn5" class="fn" id="_ftn5">[5]</a> In ODC's concurrence, it
  stated, "[ODC] concurs that deferred suspension with probation along with the following proposed conditions is
  appropriate for the admitted misconduct:&nbsp; A.&nbsp; Public Reprimand with twelve (12) months probation. . . ."&nbsp; ODC did not
  suggest any time for suspension.&nbsp; On the contrary, ODC cited several cases that provided for public reprimand with
  conditions.&nbsp; <span class="CITE"><i>Louisiana Bar Association v. St. Romain</i>,
  <a href="../SC/1990-04-30_1989-0252.htm">560 So.2d 375</a> (La. 1990)</span>; <span class="CITE"><i>In re Dennis S.
  Mann</i>, <a href="1999-03-08_98-DB-091.htm">98-DB-091</a></span>; <span class="CITE"><i>In re Dennis K. Dolbear</i>,
  <a href="1999-02-24_98-DB-061.htm">98-DB-061</a></span>; <span class="CITE"><i>In re C. Kenneth Deshotel</i>,
  <a href="1999-04-08_97-DB-063.htm">97-DB-063</a></span> and <span class="CITE"><i>In re Arden Wells</i>,
  <a href="1999-04-13_98-DB-071.htm">98-DB-071</a></span>. &nbsp; In Respondent's Petition there is no mention of deferred
  suspension and ODC did not object to the Petition.&nbsp; It appears that the parties agreed that in lieu of a deferred
  suspension Respondent would be subject to a public reprimand with conditions.&nbsp; The recommended sanction has been
  adopted from the Respondent's Petition.</p>

  <p class="footnotetext"><a href="#_ftnref6" name="_ftn6" class="fn" id="_ftn6">[6]</a> Admonition,
  <span class="CITE">94-ADB-096 (Disc. Bd. 7/20/94)</span>.&nbsp; Respondent admitted to violating Rules
  <span class="Rules">8.1(c)</span> and <span class="Rules">8.4(g)</span>.</p>

